  <bioghist id="aspace_07293eee69a95a0b46795ff9e8ff0183">
    <head>BIOGRAPHICAL NOTE</head>
<p>Lawyer; legislator.</p><p> John R. Pillion served as a New York State Assemblyman from 1941 to 1950 and United States Congressman from 1953 to 1964.</p>  </bioghist>
  <scopecontent id="aspace_473a98590363693054d8982baf861ea3">
    <head>COLLECTION DESCRIPTION</head>
<p>Correspondence, speeches, card files, news releases, legislative bills, tape recordings, clippings, scrapbooks, and questionnaires relating to Pillion's work as an assemblyman and congressman.</p><p> Included are correspondence with constituents; alphabetical card indexes of actions taken on each constituent's request; and correspondence, hearings, justifications, and working papers concerning appropriations for government departments, commissions, and agencies. Also, legislative and general correspondence and information files concerning state or local projects; the Antarctic Treaty and Pillion's trip to Antarctica in 1959; his opposition to statehood for Alaska and Hawaii; national issues; and foreign policy and international affairs. There are also copies of bills he introduced into Congress, speeches, news releases, tape recordings, questionnaires, clipping scrapbooks, and loose clippings.</p>  </scopecontent>
